<document>
	<title>Cystic-fibrosis screening in the newborn.</title>

	<author>Crossley-J-R.</author>
	<author>Berryman-C-C.</author>
	<author>Elliott-R-B.</author>

	<source>Lancet. 1977 Nov 26. 2(8048). P 1093-5.</source>

	<abstract>In a new method of testing stool samples from newborn babies for
   cystic fibrosis (C.F.), a colourless substrate, benzoyl-arginine-p-
   nitroanilide (B.A.P.N.A.), releases yellow p-nitroaniline when
   hydrolysed by trypsin. Samples from infants with C.F., who lack
   trypsin, give negligible colour. 2 infants with C.F. were detected
   among 2500 consecutive newborn babies tested. The incidence of false-
   positive results was 1.2% after the first specimen and 0.05% after
   the second specimen. A further refinement has reduced the positive
   rate to 0.1% after the first specimen (2000 samples). Tests on
   samples from 5 other older patients with untreated C.F. have yielded
   no evidence for false-negative results.</abstract>

